SARS, also known as "uncommon pneumonia", is the first well-documented HCoV-infection and SARS-CoV pathogen in human history, and the third HCoV detection.
The first SARS case was detected in Guangdong province, China, in late 2002.
The SARS pandemic has recorded 8,096 infections with 774 deaths, and has spread to several countries and continents.
Except for super-transmissions, each infection is estimated to lead to approximately two secondary infections, with a time interval of 4 to 7 days between onset of symptoms and the peak of the virus on the 10th day of illness.
