All the features of coronaviruses in nature are present in the novel SARS-CoV-2 virus.
Outside the human body, the virus is killed by household soap, which causes its protective bubble to burst. SARS-CoV-2 is closely related to the original SARS-CoV.
The organs most affected by COVID-19 are the lungs, as the virus reaches the host cells via the enzyme angiotensin-converting enzyme 2 (ACE2), which is abundant in the type II alveolar cells of the lungs.
The pathogen uses a unique exoskeleton called a pepelomer to communicate with ACE2 and enter another cell.
